\end_inset

 constructively, in a similar fashion to how we proved the existence of
 the Lebesgue measure in Chapter 1.
 In this spirit, we shall define a functional on the non-negative measurable
 simple functions and extend the domain of this functional to more complicated
 function spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:simpleFuncIntegral"

\end_inset

For any measurable simple function 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{M}_{\textnormal{sim}}\left(\X,\F\right)$
\end_inset

 with the standard representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

define, for any measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\F$
\end_inset

, the functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right):=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Immediately, we can see that our proto-integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 behaves quite nicely: it is always non-negative and since indicator functions
 are special cases of simple functions, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(\indicate_{A}\right)=\mu\left(A\right)
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, our functional satisfies the linearity property on the space
 of simple measurable functions.
 To see this we shall need the following lemma which solves a minor technical
 issue that arises due to our definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 relying on the standard representation of simple functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:lebIntDiffRep"

\end_inset

For any non-negative measurable simple function 
\begin_inset Formula $s\in\mathcal{M}_{\textnormal{sim}}\left(\X,\F\right)$
\end_inset

 with a standard representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

and another representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{i}\indicate_{B_{j}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ B_{j}\right\} _{j=1}^{J}$
\end_inset

 is a partition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right):=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{j}\mu\left(B_{j}\right).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the functional derived from a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 as in Definition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "def:simpleFuncIntegral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that both 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{j}$
\end_inset

 partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\X$
\end_inset

 and so observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right) & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(\bigcup_{j=1}^{J}\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the last equality follows by finite addivity.
 Similarly,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{j}\mu\left(B_{j}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{j}\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Now observe that since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}=\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{i}\indicate_{B_{j}}$
\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{i}=\beta_{j}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\cap B_{j}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

; conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}\cap B_{j}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and so we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\alpha_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{j}\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{J}\beta_{j}\mu\left(B_{j}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:lebIntLinearitySimpleFunc"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s,t\in\mathcal{M}_{\textnormal{sim}}\left(\X,\F\right)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

be a measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(\alpha s+\beta t\right)=\alpha\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right)+\beta\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(t\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
It is sufficient to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(\alpha s\right)=\alpha\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s+t\right)=\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right)+\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(t\right).$
\end_inset

 To show the first equality, simply notice that if 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is given by the standard representation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s=\sum_{i=1}^{I}a_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

then the standard representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha s$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 is simply
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha s=\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha a_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(\alpha s\right) & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}\alpha a_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)\\
 & =\alpha\sum_{i=1}^{I}a_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)\\
 & =\alpha\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha s=\indicate_{\emptyset}$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(\alpha s\right)=\mu\left(\emptyset\right)=0=\alpha\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
In order to prove the second equality, observe that if the standard representati
ons of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
s & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}a_{i}\indicate_{A_{i}}\\
t & =\sum_{j=1}^{J}b_{j}\indicate_{B_{j}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s+t\right) & =\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\left(a_{i}+b_{j}\right)\indicate_{A_{i}\cap B_{j}}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\left(a_{i}+b_{j}\right)\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}a_{i}\sum_{j=1}^{J}\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)+\sum_{j=1}^{J}b_{j}\sum_{i=1}^{I}\mu\left(A_{i}\cap B_{j}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{I}a_{i}\mu\left(A_{i}\right)+\sum_{j=1}^{J}b_{j}\mu\left(B_{j}\right)\\
 & =\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(s\right)+\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(t\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first equality follows from Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:simpleFunctionsAddMultiply"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the second equality due to Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:lebIntDiffRep"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and the fourth equality due to finite additivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Linearity and non-negativity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 tells us that for any simple measurable functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\leq g$
\end_inset

, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(f\right)\leq\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(g\right).
\]

\end_inset

Indeed, we can decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\left(g-f\right)+f$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g-f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 are both non-negative simple functions and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(g\right)=\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(g-f\right)+\bar{\mu}_{0}\left(f\right)
\]

\end_inset

which by non-negativity proves our claim.
 In other words, our functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\emph on
increasing 
\emph default
or 
\emph on
monotone 
\emph default
functional.
 With this final fact, we are now ready to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 to the space of non-negative measurable functions.
\end_layout

